00:10:27,632 --> 00:10:32,515
So this is the agenda of what we're hoping to cover this evening, first starting off with who is Block Power and what we do.

113
00:10:33,582 --> 00:10:38,143
Then moving on to talk a little bit about what electrification is and why we think electrification is important.

114
00:10:38,663 --> 00:10:50,966
Then moving on to how to finance electrification, next steps for homeowners, and next steps for members for the community of Medford and the camps of Tufts as a group.

115
00:10:50,986 --> 00:10:57,887
So BlockPower's mission is to make buildings smarter, greener, and healthier, or as our CEO calls it, turning buildings into Teslas.

116
00:10:58,827 --> 00:11:02,728
We do this by reducing fossil fuel consumption and pollution in building energy systems.

117
00:11:03,817 --> 00:11:06,380
And this is our founder and CEO Danelle Baird.

118
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:10,424
He grew up in a one-bedroom apartment in Brooklyn that had no heat.

119
00:11:10,945 --> 00:11:18,232
And the only way his family was able to warm their apartment in the winter was to turn on the oven at night and open the oven door.

120
00:11:18,433 --> 00:11:24,479
And his parents would do that, open the kitchen window to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning from hurting the family.

121
00:11:25,047 --> 00:11:30,956
And then they'd all retreat into the one bedroom of their apartment and no one was allowed to leave that bedroom until the next morning.

122
00:11:31,677 --> 00:11:37,867
And that was for all of Danelle's childhood basically growing up and coming out of that experience he appreciated.

123
00:11:38,659 --> 00:11:51,344
both how unfair that was and how that burden tended to fall on people who looked like him instead of people who looked like me and on lower income residents and committed himself to address the energy burden that exists.

124
00:11:51,464 --> 00:11:55,686
And as he learned more about climate change, made that his mission as well to really address climate change.

125
00:11:56,386 --> 00:12:02,809
And that's why we're all in on electrifying buildings and getting oil and gas out of building systems.

126
00:12:05,322 --> 00:12:12,305
So the way BlockPower operates, we have a customizable menu of building electrification programs and projects that we can do for communities.

127
00:12:12,545 --> 00:12:22,590
So we have BlockMaps, which is our software planning tool that allows cities, utilities, towns to get a really comprehensive understanding of the

128
00:12:23,050 --> 00:12:39,447
energy footprint of their buildings and what upgrade measures can do to reduce that footprint and how much it would cost to including to electrify every single building in the community and designing incentive programs and designing outreach campaigns with all that data.

129
00:12:39,927 --> 00:12:46,193
So we're very excited about and nearby Cambridge is the first Massachusetts client using block maps.

130
00:12:47,074 --> 00:12:54,141
We also have financing, where we've raised nearly $100 million from different sources that will allow us to finance building electrification projects.

131
00:12:54,161 --> 00:13:08,374
And the way our financing works is that we have a lease, where we tend to lease heat pumps, which is the main technology we use, which Dennis will be talking a bit more about, but really to enable electrification to happen without financing being a barrier.

132
00:13:09,054 --> 00:13:11,737
And then we have something that we like to call community-driven enablers, where

133
00:13:12,167 --> 00:13:27,494
We work on, among other things, workforce development programs where we train up people and the skills they need to do building electrification work, because we recognize that there's a shortage of skilled contractors who know how to do the type of work that we need to have done in very large numbers across the country.

134
00:13:28,254 --> 00:13:33,597
And we really focus that workforce development on underrepresented workers, ensuring a just transition.

135
00:13:34,537 --> 00:13:45,186
We also have, through our nonprofit, we have a Wi-Fi program where we help to connect underserved neighborhoods with the internet and bring them into the 21st century and all the internet has to offer.

136
00:13:46,307 --> 00:13:59,798
And then finally, part of our community engagement involves standing up community advisory boards, which really allow us to really build deep levels of trust within the community as we're working to help electrify the community and also hold us accountable to the community standards.

137
00:14:02,355 --> 00:14:07,459
This is a sampling of where we currently have have partnerships and projects up and running.

138
00:14:08,219 --> 00:14:19,788
So you see in Massachusetts, we're just starting some workforce development work here and getting started on some building electrification also New York City, New York State is where we are best known for having started in Brooklyn, and

139
00:14:20,468 --> 00:14:31,532
I think we are probably best known nationally for a partnership we have with the city of Ithaca to electrify every single building in the city of Ithaca by the year 2030, which is not too far away, thankfully.

140
00:14:32,752 --> 00:14:37,274
But also doing a lot of work in California, and as you can see, starting to work in other states as well.

141
00:14:37,454 --> 00:14:41,375
And I'm sure a year from now, there will be many more states filled in on this map.

142
