Let's go to the next slide here.

151
00:15:25,667 --> 00:15:32,755
So what is electrification and why do we care about it is what I'll be talking about for a little bit here.

152
00:15:33,852 --> 00:15:36,773
30% of greenhouse gases come from buildings.

153
00:15:37,113 --> 00:15:42,535
And that's across the US, and it's potentially even higher across the world.

154
00:15:42,595 --> 00:15:55,220
And so what we're really looking to do is getting fossil fuels out of your home in terms of your heating space and your cooling spaces, heating hot water, your cooking, and everything else that you have going on.

155
00:15:55,320 --> 00:15:59,482
And so as we know here in Massachusetts and the New England region,

156
00:16:00,103 --> 00:16:09,433
There are plenty of fossil fuels in homes and we have old buildings and we have lots of work to do in terms of electrification so I'll talk a little bit more about what that looks like.

157
00:16:12,408 --> 00:16:17,730
The four C's are really where we see the why behind electrification.

158
00:16:17,750 --> 00:16:23,593
There are obvious reasons, and I'll share a little bit more about this in just a second, around climate protection.

159
00:16:23,673 --> 00:16:26,814
And I know most of the folks here are climate concerned individuals.

160
00:16:26,894 --> 00:16:31,276
So we're excited to explore that together.

161
00:16:32,417 --> 00:16:36,879
Comfort, as you drive around New England, you notice that there,

162
00:16:37,626 --> 00:16:46,174
are tons of window AC units or a lot of apartments and homes that have never had cooling and as our climate gets warmer.

163
00:16:47,235 --> 00:16:52,200
Comfort is is a big deal clean air, as we all know, with the season that we're coming out of.

164
00:16:53,048 --> 00:16:55,729
with COVID and other things is also really important.

165
00:16:55,749 --> 00:16:59,791
So we believe there's electrification benefits for clean air as well.

166
00:16:59,891 --> 00:17:04,812
And so you get simultaneous heating, cooling, and you get more clean air in your home.

167
00:17:05,873 --> 00:17:08,194
Cancer prevention, we're really talking about that clean air.

168
00:17:08,214 --> 00:17:16,437
A lot of studies out there right now about getting rid of your gas stove and how that makes a big impact in your kitchen air quality.

169
00:17:17,177 --> 00:17:24,382
And then ultimately, we'd like to see cost cutting and energy savings as a major benefit as well.

170
00:17:24,462 --> 00:17:30,126
And I'll talk a little bit more about how that may or may not be happening in Massachusetts.

171
00:17:33,588 --> 00:17:37,051
So here are the most common existing systems we run into.

172
00:17:37,631 --> 00:17:44,736
Obviously, central boilers and heating systems, window ACs, gas ranges, gas hot water heaters.

173
00:17:44,996 --> 00:17:46,397
And we want to rip all these things out.

174
00:17:47,412 --> 00:17:50,255
and replace them with potentially heat pumps.

175
00:17:53,838 --> 00:17:56,299
Heat pumps have been thrown out there quite a bit.

176
00:17:58,161 --> 00:18:00,523
Folks are starting to understand

177
00:18:01,107 --> 00:18:06,689
the benefits and opportunities with heat pumps and just to give some background on what a heat pump is.

178
00:18:07,329 --> 00:18:10,710
I'll show on the next slide here but the heat pump was invented way back in 1856.

179
00:18:13,151 --> 00:18:15,532
And so it's been around for a very long time.

180
00:18:17,432 --> 00:18:27,894
simultaneously is able to switch between cooling and heating in one unit to keep the temperature correct in your building.

181
00:18:27,954 --> 00:18:37,437
And so we're really excited to talk about the technology advances with heat pumps and where it's headed.

182
00:18:37,537 --> 00:18:39,437
So you can go to the next slide there, Craig.

183
00:18:39,517 --> 00:18:39,757
Thanks.

184
00:18:41,677 --> 00:18:42,498
So how does it work?

185
00:18:42,658 --> 00:18:43,598
We have a cooling mode.

186
00:18:44,793 --> 00:18:50,015
which the outer unit is used as the condenser, and the inner unit is the evaporator.

187
00:18:50,716 --> 00:18:54,457
And then the inverse, we have the evaporator and condenser swapped.

188
00:18:55,258 --> 00:19:04,782
And so you may have seen this in a lot of other places in the world, like Central and South America, or I would say East Asia.

189
00:19:07,298 --> 00:19:09,079
This has been a technology that's been around forever.

190
00:19:09,579 --> 00:19:16,863
And the concerns usually for people when we talk about heat pumps are, what about this bottom section?

191
00:19:16,903 --> 00:19:17,744
What about winter?

192
00:19:18,404 --> 00:19:23,247
Are we going to be able to heat our homes when it's negative 10 degrees here in New England?

193
00:19:24,188 --> 00:19:25,548
And what's going to happen?

194
00:19:25,708 --> 00:19:29,771
Are we going to be able to pull in enough warm air

195
00:19:30,986 --> 00:19:33,688
out of that negative 10 to heat our homes?

196
00:19:33,789 --> 00:19:36,711
And is it going to be able to keep up with the chilling cold?

197
00:19:37,212 --> 00:19:38,172
The answer is yes.

198
00:19:38,232 --> 00:19:44,278
In the last three to five years, we've seen major advances in heat pump technology.

199
00:19:45,139 --> 00:19:53,546
And a lot of the heat pumps that we're installing today are actually rated for up to negative 15 or negative 30.

200
00:19:54,427 --> 00:19:57,249
And the Northeast region, as well as the Midwest,

201
00:19:58,618 --> 00:20:06,260
folks have been dumping a lot of R&D into how heat pumps are going to work in these parts of the country, because we know there are so many benefits.

202
00:20:06,340 --> 00:20:19,665
And so we've seen that technology come forward, and we expect even more in the next three to five years, technological advances from energy efficiency, heating, cooling, and being able to withstand extreme temperatures.

203
00:20:21,895 --> 00:20:28,419
On the next page here, I'll talk about a quick study in BC, British Columbia.

204
00:20:28,719 --> 00:20:31,861
Canada actually has one of the cleanest grids in the world.

205
00:20:32,782 --> 00:20:39,466
And this study was done in British Columbia about heat pumps and the effect they make on the climate.

206
00:20:39,506 --> 00:20:43,308
So they're looking at the alternatives of oil and gas for homes.

207
00:20:43,928 --> 00:20:47,831
And they're seeing that compared to oil, it's about 1% of CO2 emissions.

208
00:20:50,123 --> 00:20:51,803
compared to a house heated from oil.

209
00:20:52,744 --> 00:20:53,644
That's a big deal.

210
00:20:55,044 --> 00:21:04,047
Now, there are some challenges here with the last C, which is the cost, which may come up in the questions later.

211
00:21:05,447 --> 00:21:12,969
We can get to it then, but I'll just say the excitement at BlockPower is that the

212
00:21:14,228 --> 00:21:35,351
The triple bottom line of saving the planet, saving people money, and giving them ultimately a better experience in their home is what we're going after and it's a vision that we see coming to fruition today, and going to be much more clear in the years to come, especially with the investment in the infrastructure.

213
00:21:36,672 --> 00:21:38,433
That's all I'll say about heat pumps for now.

214
00:21:39,213 --> 00:21:50,236
I'll jump to one other piece before I hand it back to Craig, which is when we talk about electrification and turning buildings into Teslas, we're not just talking about the heating and cooling systems.

215
00:21:51,177 --> 00:21:55,878
While that is really important and that's one of the most central ways that we're burning fossil fuels inside of our homes,

216
00:21:56,653 --> 00:21:57,394
There are other ways too.

217
00:21:57,574 --> 00:22:18,325
So we're looking at on the left side, you're getting what is pretty common now in some new construction, which is a tankless water heater, all powered by electric, where you can have a tanked water heater, that is a heat pump hot water heater, and replace that for your natural gas burning hot water heater.

218
00:22:19,426 --> 00:22:22,928
There's also geothermal, which is another form of heat pump.

219
00:22:23,588 --> 00:22:32,979
that is really exciting and becoming more and more accessible by digging boreholes into the ground and pulling heating and cooling from the earth.

220
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:38,345
So very similar to heat pump technology, just making some more holes in your backyard.

221
00:22:39,511 --> 00:22:45,934
And then, of course, for cooking, I just recently went to an induction range in my house.

222
00:22:46,034 --> 00:22:49,336
Thank you, Mass Save, for the generous incentive.

223
00:22:50,356 --> 00:22:51,537
And I haven't missed a beat.

224
00:22:51,637 --> 00:22:52,117
I love it.

225
00:22:52,357 --> 00:22:53,258
It's been excellent.

226
00:22:53,358 --> 00:22:59,260
And we can move away from having a gas stove, a gas range in my home and in yours as well.

227
00:22:59,380 --> 00:23:00,821
And then, of course, solar panels.

228
00:23:01,522 --> 00:23:06,524
We want to put as much solar, wind, renewable energy out there as much as possible.

229
00:23:06,684 --> 00:23:08,825
So those are some other electrification opportunities.

230
00:23:13,132 --> 00:23:17,573
And I think that comes back to me on how we pay for all of this.

231
00:23:19,653 --> 00:23:27,555
So first off, I think Massachusetts has one of, if not the most, generous rebate systems and incentive systems in the country through MassSave.

232
00:23:28,695 --> 00:23:32,736
Some of the things that you can look forward to if you're pursuing electrification of your home.

233
00:23:33,896 --> 00:23:37,197
If you do the whole house heat pumps on heat pumps, there's a $10,000 rebate.

234
00:23:39,566 --> 00:23:48,870
If you do a partial house rebate, you can get up to $1,250 per ton, up to $10,000 for doing part of your home over to heat pumps.

235
00:23:50,271 --> 00:24:01,256
There's also heat loans that are available, which are seven-year, 0% interest loans that can go up to $25,000 presently, and that number is set to increase pretty soon as I understand it.

236
00:24:03,577 --> 00:24:05,758
And then if you're doing other things like insulation,

237
00:24:06,305 --> 00:24:08,369
in your home, which is strongly recommended.

238
00:24:08,390 --> 00:24:11,496
Actually, I think it required to get the whole house rebate.

239
00:24:11,516 --> 00:24:14,883
75% of the cost of installation are covered.

240
00:24:15,448 --> 00:24:18,870
And these are all for market rate customers, for income eligible customers.

241
00:24:18,890 --> 00:24:31,975
100% of switching over to heat pumps and 100% of the cost of insulation are covered by MassAve, which are the, you know, fees that are, MassAve is funded by fees that you pay in your utility bills.

242
00:24:32,015 --> 00:24:40,819
So it's taking advantage of these incentives and rebates is really getting your money's worth for money that you and all of the other rate payers in our state are contributing to their monthly energy bills.

243
00:24:42,764 --> 00:24:52,928
We also, as folks know, just passed a very exciting climate bill called the Inflation Reduction Act recently through Congress, which has a whole suite of programs.

244
00:24:52,948 --> 00:24:54,388
We're going to talk about a couple of them.

245
00:24:55,268 --> 00:25:07,733
But just to give you a sense of the scope, it's funding electrification upgrades in low and moderate income communities, home energy retrofits, EPOM installations, also incentivizing newly constructed homes, and then also working on commercial

246
00:25:08,926 --> 00:25:09,626
commercial real estate.

247
00:25:10,267 --> 00:25:22,632
We're going to zero in on just three three chunks of this, the homes, the home energy performance based rebates, HERA, the high efficiency electric home rebate program, and then a tax credit.

248
00:25:22,852 --> 00:25:34,777
And just to speak of the tax credit, it's a fairly state that's kind of the simplest, that provides a tax credit of up to 30% from the cost of electrification projects up to $3,200 per year.

249
00:25:35,637 --> 00:25:37,638
And that annual credit limit resets every year.

250
00:25:37,678 --> 00:25:38,078
So if you

251
00:25:38,706 --> 00:25:40,967
switch your heating system over to heat pumps one year.

252
00:25:40,987 --> 00:25:46,029
And then the next year you get, you know, an electric heat pump, hot water system.

253
00:25:47,069 --> 00:25:54,212
You could get a whole new up to $3,200 credit on your taxes each year, which you're doing those as separate projects.

254
00:25:56,253 --> 00:25:57,654
To speak a little bit more about HERA.

255
00:25:58,694 --> 00:26:02,816
So this is really targeted at low and moderate income residents.

256
00:26:03,896 --> 00:26:05,417
And unlike the

257
00:26:06,344 --> 00:26:10,966
Tax credit we talked about, which is, because it's a tax credit, it's unlimited.

258
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:13,527
This is a grant or a rebate.

259
00:26:13,567 --> 00:26:16,128
So there's a finite amount of money that each state gets.

260
00:26:16,268 --> 00:26:19,450
Massachusetts will get $72 million to pass out.

261
00:26:20,890 --> 00:26:28,334
And this is really targeted at, again, households who are between 80% and 150% of area median income.

262
00:26:29,454 --> 00:26:35,357
But at the peak, there's a $14,000 maximum rebate that a resident can receive

263
00:26:36,300 --> 00:26:36,880
from HERA.

264
00:26:37,781 --> 00:26:44,704
And again, this is targeting both single family and multifamily, where at least half of the residents are low and moderate income.

265
00:26:45,224 --> 00:26:53,807
And you can see how much you get off of heat pumps and hot water, heat pump hot water and clothes dryers and so on down the row here.

266
00:26:55,668 --> 00:26:57,089
And then homes,

267
00:26:57,802 --> 00:27:01,984
is a program that serves both market rate and low and moderate income residents.

268
00:27:02,024 --> 00:27:06,326
Massachusetts is getting almost identical amount of money here, $73 million to disperse.

269
00:27:07,046 --> 00:27:18,752
And so for both of these programs, for HOMES and HERA, our state energy office, the Department of Energy Resources, is ultimately going to be putting out regulations around exactly how this money is going to be distributed.

270
00:27:18,772 --> 00:27:23,894
They're still waiting for federal guidance from the Federal Department of Energy on how to create those regulations.

271
00:27:23,954 --> 00:27:27,376
So there's not perfect clarity on how this will all work out.

272
00:27:28,159 --> 00:27:39,235
But this is our best understanding of the law, which is basically the more energy that you save, the more money you'll be able to get back from homes.

273
00:27:41,364 --> 00:27:49,790
And then finally, we do want to put in the plug for our own lease that we offer consumers, which we do a 15-year lease.

274
00:27:50,050 --> 00:27:51,471
That's how we finance heat pumps.

275
00:27:51,491 --> 00:27:53,012
So you don't buy the heat pumps from us.

276
00:27:53,132 --> 00:27:58,215
You lease them, which means we own the system and we cover the operations and maintenance of it.

277
00:27:58,275 --> 00:28:01,738
Your average heat pump gets a 10-year warranty from the manufacturer.

278
00:28:01,778 --> 00:28:09,183
We extend that warranty to the full 15-year period of the lease, and we guarantee performance over that 15-year time span.

279
00:28:10,420 --> 00:28:13,701
We have two maintenance visits per year that are scheduled.

280
00:28:13,861 --> 00:28:19,802
And if we need to come more frequently than that because of any issues with technology, we will do that.

281
00:28:20,682 --> 00:28:23,862
And this lease was really designed with low and moderate income residents in mind.

282
00:28:24,463 --> 00:28:25,663
It's a zero money down lease.

283
00:28:26,663 --> 00:28:29,223
We can build into the lease deferred maintenance costs.

284
00:28:29,243 --> 00:28:35,104
So people have to address now tube wiring or mold or asbestos or a leaky roof in order to electrify their home.

285
00:28:35,685 --> 00:28:37,925
We can do that work up front for free.

286
00:28:39,295 --> 00:28:44,039
and build in the cost of that work over the 15 years as part of the lease.

287
00:28:44,859 --> 00:28:46,701
And finally, we don't put a lien on the building.

288
00:28:47,261 --> 00:28:53,186
So there's no risk for a homeowner that if they don't hit a monthly payment, they're going to lose their home.

289
00:28:54,186 --> 00:28:56,508
We make no claim on the home as collateral.

290
00:28:59,591 --> 00:29:04,054
And then I'll kick it over to Dennis to talk more about next steps for homeowners.

291
00:29:04,935 --> 00:29:05,275
Thanks, Craig.

292
00:29:07,770 --> 00:29:18,099
All of that is fantastic and I think everybody wants to get those rebates and electrify and reduce their costs and see greenhouse gas emissions reductions.

293
00:29:19,741 --> 00:29:24,926
The question now is what do I do if I want to heat pump or what do I do if I want to electrify my home?

294
00:29:26,087 --> 00:29:27,248
So building electrification

295
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:33,503
I should maybe change the slide to is a complex process, not can be.

296
00:29:34,383 --> 00:29:40,646
You have to work with all these different groups as the building owner or homeowner to figure all these different pieces out.

297
00:29:40,786 --> 00:29:49,891
You've got the government and utility incentives, as well as permitting, planning and engineering, evaluations, energy studies, assessments.

298
00:29:50,051 --> 00:29:53,693
You've got construction and contractors that you've got to work with and find.

299
00:29:54,373 --> 00:29:57,235
You're going to buy, lease, finance the equipment.

300
00:29:58,085 --> 00:30:08,511
you're not only gonna talk to the manufacturer, you're probably gonna be in contact with some sort of lender or financer, and then potentially connect all those pieces together with broadband access.

301
00:30:08,571 --> 00:30:13,013
And so connect those to the cloud to make sure they all work and get operations and maintenance updates.

302
00:30:14,274 --> 00:30:19,457
All of that is something that you as the homeowner would have to potentially manage yourself.

303
00:30:20,637 --> 00:30:25,040
And on top of everything else you have going on in life, it's a big challenge.

304
00:30:25,915 --> 00:30:35,900
So we see that, and we know that this process, while laid out here in four steps, could be very straightforward.

305
00:30:35,920 --> 00:30:37,861
But there are a lot of barriers to this process.

306
00:30:39,422 --> 00:30:40,162
One is time.

307
00:30:40,182 --> 00:30:49,547
And the other main one we see is just competency around what you're looking for and how to get it done.

308
00:30:52,223 --> 00:31:04,652
when you're going through the scope, and you're finding contractors, and then you're designing the system, and then you're actually getting the system online, it comes with many challenges.

309
00:31:04,832 --> 00:31:11,836
You're managing multiple parties, and you're confirming a lot of different pieces that you've potentially never done before.

310
00:31:12,397 --> 00:31:20,623
And so BlockPower decided to take all that complication on, and to Craig's point at the top of the presentation,

311
00:31:22,001 --> 00:31:39,554
Because we are so focused on low and moderate income neighborhoods and those who maybe are disadvantaged or maybe not as focused on by these incentive programs, we decided to step in between there.

312
00:31:39,634 --> 00:31:46,940
And so BlockPower inserts themselves in this complex process to make it a turnkey solution.

313
00:31:47,962 --> 00:31:58,146
So we do all the planning and engineering, construction, contracting, equipment purchasing, financing, lending, broadband access if necessary, and government utility incentives and permits.

314
00:31:58,286 --> 00:32:05,409
So you hire BlockPower as your one-stop shop, and we become the experts and consultants for you to get all this done.

315
00:32:05,449 --> 00:32:10,531
You're a project manager, you're a contract manager, so on and so forth.

316
00:32:10,611 --> 00:32:13,452
And really, on top of that,

317
00:32:14,900 --> 00:32:26,164
focused on delivering a great product for you and a system that will last as long as least and hopefully beyond for the comfort of your home.

318
00:32:26,264 --> 00:32:35,887
And so there are things that are not on here, like our tools, our tech tools and our kind of acumen around how to engage with communities.

319
00:32:35,987 --> 00:32:39,068
But all in all, we're looking at a turnkey solution.

320
00:32:46,731 --> 00:32:47,251
Thanks, Dennis.

321
00:32:47,352 --> 00:33:01,083
And so I'll be talking about next steps for community campus, but very happy to go back to the earlier slide for folks who want to do it themselves if people have questions about that and recommendations on the process.

322
00:33:03,765 --> 00:33:09,911
So from the quick research I did, it looks like the city of Medford

323
00:33:11,152 --> 00:33:16,737
Building is responsible for about 66%, almost 2 thirds of emissions.

324
00:33:18,779 --> 00:33:28,467
And Medford does have a strategy of building electrification strategy 2.1 to provide tools and resources to support fuel switching and energy efficiency retrofits.

325
00:33:30,249 --> 00:33:35,874
With Tufts, natural gas burn on campus is responsible for 42% of campus emissions in 2019.

326
00:33:37,885 --> 00:33:50,996
Tufts had a lot of things, a lot of commitments they've signed on the website, but I was not able to find any specific strategy about building electrification, so it's quite possible they have one, and I just didn't see it on the interwebs.

327
00:33:52,798 --> 00:33:57,182
But yeah, just wanted to give a sense as to what Medford and Tufts' current situation is.

328
00:33:58,003 --> 00:34:03,007
And as folks are thinking about as a community, you know, how one might move forward,

329
00:34:04,258 --> 00:34:10,040
we really recommend as a first step setting a building electrification goal or goals.

330
00:34:10,220 --> 00:34:17,683
So one clear step would be to say that we're not going to put, not allow any new gas hookups in any new buildings that come online.

331
00:34:17,703 --> 00:34:23,605
You know, that's I think always one of the safest bets when you're in a hole, stop digging, right?

332
00:34:23,626 --> 00:34:31,509
So this is stopping making the problem worse by saying for new buildings, we're not going to allow them to have gas in these new buildings as they come online.

333
00:34:33,303 --> 00:34:39,805
10 communities were allowed via the legislation that passed the state legislature this past summer.

334
00:34:41,205 --> 00:34:48,007
In theory, 10 communities will be allowed to undertake a pilot program to do just that, to ban new gas hookups in their communities.

335
00:34:48,087 --> 00:34:53,528
Which 10 communities and how exactly that's going to work out is being worked out still.

336
00:34:54,088 --> 00:34:56,929
It's possible that they may ultimately allow more than 10 communities.

337
00:34:56,949 --> 00:35:01,030
I think it's a matter of when, not if, but they may start even allowing more than 10 communities.

338
00:35:02,477 --> 00:35:04,146
they haven't already could get on that waiting list.

339
00:35:06,020 --> 00:35:08,141
But then really, that's the easy part, right?

340
00:35:08,202 --> 00:35:09,763
It's safe for the new buildings.

341
00:35:09,923 --> 00:35:16,988
We're not going to do this when you have a huge existing building stock that has gas and oil already in those systems.

342
00:35:17,328 --> 00:35:31,157
And so we really recommend for both the campus and for the city to think about, do we want to say by, for instance, the year 2030, we're going to electrify a certain percentage of our buildings or a certain number of our buildings?

343
00:35:31,698 --> 00:35:35,060
And we're working with communities that are both looking at a percentage number or saying,

344
00:35:35,541 --> 00:35:37,342
we're going to take on 1,000 buildings by 2030.

345
00:35:37,622 --> 00:35:45,646
The most audacious or the most comprehensive way to do this is to set a goal of saying we're going to electrify all of our buildings by this year.

346
00:35:46,386 --> 00:35:59,573
The fastest timeline that are on our radar are saying we're going to electrify all of our buildings by 2030, which both Ithaca, New York, and Menlo Park, California have committed to do and have shown a lot of power to work with them in partnership around.

347
00:36:01,774 --> 00:36:12,002
A recommended but not necessary step is finding and building electrification partner, which Black Power is, of course, happy to be considered to help you think through how to do this.

348
00:36:12,142 --> 00:36:14,264
But, you know, some may choose to do it on their own.

349
00:36:14,584 --> 00:36:17,507
And that's, you know, the climate needs us all to stretch ourselves.

350
00:36:17,527 --> 00:36:20,809
So more power to you if you want to take that path.

351
00:36:20,889 --> 00:36:22,771
And then the third step is to create a plan to do that.

352
00:36:23,271 --> 00:36:27,595
As we referenced, our mapping software is a particularly helpful way to jumpstart such planning.

353
00:36:28,355 --> 00:36:29,036
Some may choose to make

354
00:36:29,409 --> 00:36:32,051
make a plan before they find building electrification partner.

355
00:36:32,071 --> 00:36:36,534
I think that's wise in some ways and more challenging in other ways.

356
00:36:37,895 --> 00:36:40,677
But either way, we stand ready to assist.

357
00:36:41,238 --> 00:36:44,660
But also, again, not trying to push our services too hard here.

358
00:36:44,700 --> 00:36:48,263
So if people want to charge on their own, that's what the climate needs.

359
00:36:48,303 --> 00:36:52,286
So however it gets done, we want to make sure that the buildings are getting electrified.

360
00:36:54,648 --> 00:37:03,651
And finally, just a small note that we are also looking for a small number of universities that are looking to engage both their campus and their local community in ambitious decarbonization goals.

361
00:37:05,192 --> 00:37:13,415
Our CEO has a vision of 10 universities around the country that are really, really charging full speed ahead with building decarbonization.

362
00:37:13,475 --> 00:37:18,376
So if folks connected from Tufts are interested in learning more about that, please feel free to reach out to us.

363
00:37:21,275 --> 00:37:24,056
share some early seeds on that idea.

364
00:37:25,357 --> 00:37:41,985
Again, just as I mentioned, I think one particularly helpful step is our block map software, which we would be happy to make available to the city of Medford at a cost, if that's something that folks desire.

365
00:37:43,763 --> 00:37:52,147
And again, it's a really, really helpful building visualization tool that allows you to understand the full scope of the building stack in Medford or any other community.

366
00:37:52,947 --> 00:38:00,330
And then really design program that meets your goals around environmental justice or cost savings and building electrification.

367
00:38:00,970 --> 00:38:05,652
And also we have a tool, a companion tool for building owners, our incident building report.

368
00:38:06,673 --> 00:38:09,734
But with that, yeah, we'd love to pivot to the question and answer session.

369
00:38:10,294 --> 00:38:11,035
We've got a number there.

370
00:38:14,485 --> 00:38:17,146
And Bob, are you all handling facilitating that or?

371
00:38:17,166 --> 00:38:19,187
This is Bob Payne.

372
00:38:19,527 --> 00:38:31,611
There was a question, you mentioned costs early on and how does the cost of a heat pump system compare to current fossil fuel systems?

373
00:38:31,871 --> 00:38:33,712
I don't know if you were going to get back to that.

374
00:38:36,753 --> 00:38:37,253
Yeah, so.

375
00:38:40,092 --> 00:38:50,940
It's in terms of, I honestly don't know how much a new fossil fuel system costs these days, because I'm not interested in buying one and we don't serve customers who are.

376
00:38:52,221 --> 00:39:01,208
We'll say that for an average 2,000 square foot home, if you do a multi-split system, that's in the $25,000 to $35,000 range is our estimate.

377
00:39:01,228 --> 00:39:04,110
A duct, if you already have ducts in your home,

378
00:39:10,199 --> 00:39:24,830
For a similar size home, the cost could be 30% to 50% less expensive than that if you could tap into existing central air ducts that you already have online, or even, I think, forest heat air as well.

379
00:39:26,312 --> 00:39:34,118
And a ground source heat pump, if folks are looking to do that, is more in the $30,000 to $50,000 range.

380
00:39:34,198 --> 00:39:39,081
So a lot of that depends on the geology of your area.

381
00:39:41,321 --> 00:39:44,824
And again, we talked about the incentives.

382
00:39:44,844 --> 00:39:47,727
So that's the pre-incentive cost.

383
00:39:48,228 --> 00:39:57,116
So obviously in Massachusetts, again, if you do the whole home, you're talking taking $10,000 off from the top and then with all the additional incentives from the Inflation Reduction Act on top of that.

384
00:39:57,156 --> 00:39:58,677
But Dennis, do you want to add to that?

385
00:40:00,599 --> 00:40:05,804
Yeah, I'll just add that we get these questions pretty often.

386
00:40:08,684 --> 00:40:13,508
The challenge with answering them, we're not skirting around them because they don't want to answer them.

387
00:40:13,588 --> 00:40:24,357
The challenge is that we have, there are old homes in this region of the country that need more than just a rip and replacement of their heating and cooling system engine, if you will.

388
00:40:25,017 --> 00:40:27,519
There is air sealing that needs to be done.

389
00:40:27,539 --> 00:40:29,381
There's insulation that needs to be done.

390
00:40:30,261 --> 00:40:31,682
And if anybody has done

391
00:40:32,463 --> 00:40:44,270
any home projects or construction, the minute you start opening anything up, you always find other things that potentially have maintenance issues or other challenges for ripping and replacing.

392
00:40:44,310 --> 00:40:56,937
And so that is why we designed our, personally for BlockPower, that's why we designed our lease product, because within that lease, you're able to actually finance all of those other things that I'm talking about, whether it's

393
00:40:57,377 --> 00:41:11,269
replacing old wiring or doing insulation or other pieces to be able to get your electrification in your home, we can roll that into the lease and make it one monthly lower payment.

394
00:41:11,469 --> 00:41:14,272
And so the price of

395
00:41:15,245 --> 00:41:18,526
heat pumps has gone down significantly and we foresee it continuing to go down.

396
00:41:18,766 --> 00:41:29,310
And I think the incentives are making it very lucrative to where it's potentially comparing apples to apples when it comes to cost for natural gas or oil systems.

397
00:41:32,518 --> 00:41:42,141
What about the ongoing, let's say you get the system installed, what is the ongoing cost of just supplying the heating and cooling?

398
00:41:42,601 --> 00:41:55,405
Of course, I have a house, for example, it's gas-fired boiler, steam radiators, no cooling except for in-window air condition, so I really sweat during the summer.

399
00:41:56,385 --> 00:41:59,706
And they have steam radiators in the winter, but is it

400
00:42:00,909 --> 00:42:02,009
would I save money?

401
00:42:02,669 --> 00:42:04,930
Obviously, I'd be more comfortable in the summer.

402
00:42:04,950 --> 00:42:10,871
Yeah, I can answer that.

403
00:42:10,971 --> 00:42:26,614
So I'll say you'll save energy, but depending on what rates you're on and depending on what time of year and how much energy you're using, if you decide to

404
00:42:27,778 --> 00:42:34,160
just because you can, Bob, if you decide to cool your house to 65 degrees all summer, I'll tell you, you definitely won't save money.

405
00:42:35,140 --> 00:42:39,121
And you'll save money by sweating a little bit more in the summer.

406
00:42:39,181 --> 00:42:47,022
And so it really depends on a case-to-case basis, whether you will see clear, significant financial savings.

407
00:42:47,943 --> 00:42:53,744
We do project on most of our projects a clear energy savings to make the switch to electric.

408
00:42:59,467 --> 00:43:00,908
Great, thanks guys.

409
00:43:01,348 --> 00:43:08,011
Bob, if you don't mind, I'm going to ask a few from, we've gotten some really great questions in the Q&A.

410
00:43:08,872 --> 00:43:09,972
All right.

411
00:43:12,433 --> 00:43:23,858
So first question for you guys, with the newer heat pumps that can handle heating when temperatures are below negative 10 degrees, would one also need a secondary backup heat system?

412
00:43:25,199 --> 00:43:26,860
I can answer this part, Dennis.

413
00:43:28,223 --> 00:43:32,705
So, you know, I think it's really what you want to optimize, right?

414
00:43:33,205 --> 00:43:47,332
If you want to optimize absolutely having heat, whether or not the power goes out, then I think, you know, there could be some wisdom to keeping a gas system online in your house.

415
00:43:47,352 --> 00:43:56,617
That does mean you've got the starter light kind of always on and ready to go, and you're still burning a low level of fossil fuels in your home, and you're still leaking a small level

416
00:43:57,752 --> 00:43:58,673
fossil fuels in your home.

417
00:43:59,754 --> 00:44:06,539
But if the power goes out and a really cold day, you're going to be pretty well guaranteed to still have a heating system.

418
00:44:07,360 --> 00:44:23,053
If instead you want to optimize climate impacts and health of your family and take the risk on not having heat if there's a big storm and the power goes out, then I would say you would want to remove the system.

419
00:44:23,093 --> 00:44:25,214
So it's really a values

420
00:44:26,456 --> 00:44:27,897
choice and what you want to prioritize.

421
00:44:28,737 --> 00:44:50,064
Again, I think that the health impact studies that I've seen so far are much more about the harms of cooking with gas in your kitchen, which is a place that you tend to spend a lot more time in than the health impacts of burning fossil fuels in your basement, which people don't tend to usually hang out next to the boiler or their furnace for hours on end.

422
00:44:51,044 --> 00:44:52,365
But that stuff is in your home.

423
00:44:53,367 --> 00:44:56,549
And I think that there's a health advantage of getting that out of your home.

424
00:44:57,310 --> 00:45:10,779
But again, when we're on the electric system, unless you also invest in a battery storage system, which some folks have the ability to do and may choose to do, you might want to maximize that system for you.

425
00:45:12,680 --> 00:45:15,662
Yeah, I'll just add, there are potentially

426
00:45:17,745 --> 00:45:23,107
incentives or programs that will pay you to get those fossil fuels out of your house completely.

427
00:45:23,767 --> 00:45:27,629
And so I would explore those depending on where you live and what that looks like.

428
00:45:31,270 --> 00:45:32,150
Thanks.

429
00:45:33,651 --> 00:45:39,373
And then next question, what is involved in the house as far as installation?

430
00:45:39,393 --> 00:45:44,775
Question is, do they need to go into all of the rooms and put in tubes or anything else?

431
00:45:46,123 --> 00:45:49,104
So again, this depends on what kind of system you wanna have.

432
00:45:50,904 --> 00:45:56,045
If you already have duct work in your house, then they can just tap right into that.

433
00:45:56,526 --> 00:46:09,409
And so you're switching out, basically like the equipment that you have air conditioning, your central AC represents basically gets swapped out for very similar looking equipment that is now a heat pump.

434
00:46:09,489 --> 00:46:14,410
If you're doing mini splits instead, then in every room you have kind of a large box

435
00:46:15,162 --> 00:46:22,305
that would be mounted onto the wall, not in every room, but in every room you want to have heat pumps circulating air through.

436
00:46:22,325 --> 00:46:25,106
You would have a mini split system that would go there.

437
00:46:25,126 --> 00:46:29,408
But yeah, Dennis, I know you also have recently done this.

438
00:46:29,428 --> 00:46:32,869
I don't know if you want to add to that.

439
00:46:32,949 --> 00:46:35,030
Yeah, again, it just depends.

440
00:46:35,722 --> 00:46:38,324
Depends on if there's a backup in the house, if there's not.

441
00:46:38,704 --> 00:46:52,872
And like I mentioned earlier, a lot of different pieces go into making sure that if we do replace a system with heat pumps, we're making sure that they're going to work as effectively as possible.

442
00:46:52,992 --> 00:46:57,155
So upgrading wiring, insulation, weatherization, other things.

443
00:47:00,603 --> 00:47:01,003
Thank you.

444
00:47:02,543 --> 00:47:02,884
Great.

445
00:47:03,384 --> 00:47:05,664
And what happens when when the lease ends?

446
00:47:05,844 --> 00:47:07,745
Who owns the equipment after that?

447
00:47:10,725 --> 00:47:11,386
Yeah, great question.

448
00:47:12,926 --> 00:47:17,807
The lease ends and we actually hand the equipment over to the homeowner.

449
00:47:19,588 --> 00:47:21,088
And so there's a

450
00:47:21,899 --> 00:47:27,260
There's more details in the lease than that, but more or less it becomes the equipment owned by the homeowner.

451
00:47:27,280 --> 00:47:47,206
And one of the things that we are working on, because technology is advancing so much, personally at BlockPower, is whether there will be upgrade options in that lease to where you could upgrade to potentially new technology, so you're not locked into the same thing for 15 years if you want to upgrade to something that just came out,

452
00:47:47,910 --> 00:47:51,752
there's new opportunities that we see out there to save you energy and to save greenhouse gas emissions.

453
00:47:56,235 --> 00:47:56,475
Great.

454
00:47:56,575 --> 00:48:00,297
And we have a question related to the mass save incentives.

455
00:48:01,538 --> 00:48:10,163
Are they going to continue in 2023 at the same rate and the IRS tax credits would start for systems installed in 2023?

456
00:48:10,463 --> 00:48:10,643
Correct?

457
00:48:10,683 --> 00:48:10,743
Yes.

458
00:48:14,767 --> 00:48:19,850
So starting January 1st, 2023, the tax credits start.

459
00:48:20,671 --> 00:48:27,054
And yes, you can layer them on top of the $10,000 mass save incentive.

460
00:48:27,114 --> 00:48:34,639
It's possible that that incentive will change as the IRA comes online, but at present, all signs point to it remaining.

461
00:48:36,340 --> 00:48:38,441
But yeah, they can definitely be layered on top of each other.

462
00:48:38,461 --> 00:48:41,423
Great, thank you.

463
00:48:42,380 --> 00:48:47,061
And I'm still talking about MassSave.

464
00:48:47,121 --> 00:48:57,003
Someone had a question here about if they know someone who has promised the MassSave rebate and has never gotten it, despite much effort to send them information.

465
00:48:57,083 --> 00:48:58,143
Have you run into this?

466
00:48:58,523 --> 00:49:00,224
Do you have any advice for that person?

467
00:49:03,004 --> 00:49:06,885
I have not personally run into this, but I mean, I think that the first step

468
00:49:08,403 --> 00:49:11,485
I would say would be to call the contractor that obviously did the work.

469
00:49:11,525 --> 00:49:15,807
I'm sure that you've probably been in touch with them more times than you can count.

470
00:49:15,927 --> 00:49:22,671
But I think if they're not doing what they need to do to get you that, then I would say call your utility.

471
00:49:22,691 --> 00:49:31,335
And if that doesn't work, I would say call your state legislator, your state rep, or your state senator, and get them on the case and explain to them what happened.

472
00:49:31,375 --> 00:49:36,078
And I think folks getting a call from an elected official

473
00:49:37,280 --> 00:49:40,403
or even someone on their staff, I think it would be a pretty big escalation.

474
00:49:40,443 --> 00:49:43,966
They would hopefully turn their attention to that more readily.

475
00:49:46,389 --> 00:49:47,350
Great.

476
00:49:48,891 --> 00:49:54,716
And going back to questions about a lease, what happens if you sell the house before the end of the lease?

477
00:49:56,818 --> 00:49:57,519
Yeah.

478
00:49:57,599 --> 00:49:59,561
So the lease has a buyout.

479
00:50:01,093 --> 00:50:04,415
if you're selling the home, but it's also transferable.

480
00:50:04,536 --> 00:50:10,039
So depending on the preference of the seller, we can go either way.

481
00:50:12,521 --> 00:50:12,761
Great.

482
00:50:13,102 --> 00:50:13,402
All right.

483
00:50:13,902 --> 00:50:20,827
And just a couple more before I turn it over to our panelists, who I know are bursting with questions.

484
00:50:24,347 --> 00:50:29,551
attendee here writes, I have an old house with a very old gas boiler and forced hot water radiators.

485
00:50:29,631 --> 00:50:39,617
So far, the contractors I have talked to seem to indicate that I need to install a mini split in each room, which would take up a lot of space in rooms that already have the giant radiators.

486
00:50:40,338 --> 00:50:48,163
It seems super expensive and intimidating to consider doing this, which would require holes and walls all over with a new build that it seems easy.

487
00:50:48,763 --> 00:50:51,405
Do you have solutions to streamline and deal with these issues?

488
00:50:57,010 --> 00:50:57,270
Greg?

489
00:50:59,971 --> 00:51:03,712
Yeah, I mean, we are not magicians, unfortunately.

490
00:51:03,792 --> 00:51:15,056
So yeah, I mean, again, having hot water radiators in every room is also, I think, has historically been an imposition.

491
00:51:15,516 --> 00:51:20,837
And yeah, I mean, the nice thing is that the mini splits are on the wall, so they don't take up floor space.

492
00:51:20,877 --> 00:51:22,358
You can have them above a couch.

493
00:51:22,398 --> 00:51:23,718
You can have them above a dresser.

494
00:51:23,738 --> 00:51:25,279
You can have them above a bed.

495
00:51:26,213 --> 00:51:31,918
So it doesn't interfere with furniture in the same way that radiators tend to do.

496
00:51:31,938 --> 00:51:38,542
But at the end of the day, if you want to heat your home, there is equipment that needs to be present.

497
00:51:39,423 --> 00:51:43,706
I think another option would be to build a ducted system.

498
00:51:44,467 --> 00:51:52,092
That obviously has a lot of costs involved if you don't already have ducts in your house to build out ducts, but that would certainly be an option to consider.

499
00:51:52,112 --> 00:51:55,415
But again, I think that becomes a much more invasive process.

500
00:51:55,908 --> 00:52:00,151
folks being in your home for a lot longer to do that, to building out the ducted system.

501
00:52:02,532 --> 00:52:06,675
Unfortunately, I don't know there's an easy fix for it.

502
00:52:06,815 --> 00:52:21,404
I've heard talk about in the medium term, there may be ways to boil that water with heat pumps and to use existing radiator technology.

503
00:52:21,584 --> 00:52:24,006
But I think that's a pretty decent

504
00:52:24,373 --> 00:52:27,495
time away from being a commercialized technology.

505
00:52:27,515 --> 00:52:29,776
So I personally, I do have radiators.

506
00:52:29,856 --> 00:52:31,356
I'm planning to get heat pumps pretty soon.

507
00:52:31,377 --> 00:52:32,717
I'm not planning to wait for that.

508
00:52:36,119 --> 00:52:36,599
Thank you.

509
00:52:36,899 --> 00:52:43,182
And one more for you guys before I send it over to Bob and Paul and other committee members.

510
00:52:45,383 --> 00:52:48,545
One person writes, OK, I'm a homeowner and I'm convinced.

511
00:52:50,066 --> 00:52:51,867
If you could give this person

512
00:52:52,923 --> 00:52:55,946
one next step, what would it be for them to get started?

513
00:52:58,728 --> 00:53:00,790
Well, it's a little bit of a softball.

514
00:53:02,451 --> 00:53:10,938
You could call BlockPower and inquire, or I should say, go to our website, inquire right on there, put in your info, and somebody will reach out to you.

515
00:53:12,439 --> 00:53:19,905
And I think I saw another question, or maybe we didn't say it earlier, BlockPower works

516
00:53:20,603 --> 00:53:30,651
with MassSave and partners with all the great energy services providers in Massachusetts to really support all the great work that's going on.

517
00:53:30,671 --> 00:53:33,113
Craig was talking about the financing and some other things.

518
00:53:33,713 --> 00:53:40,798
And so MassSave is a great place to start to look for resources as well.

519
00:53:42,640 --> 00:53:43,380
All right, thank you.

520
00:53:44,974 --> 00:53:49,139
At this point, I'll invite Bob to come and ask any other questions.

521
00:53:49,219 --> 00:53:58,769
And I know Paul, who is also an Energy and Environment Committee member, has a lot of questions that he's been so kind to collect from others.

522
00:53:58,829 --> 00:54:01,132
So Paul, feel free to chime in as well.

523
00:54:02,333 --> 00:54:06,138
Bob, I'll just ask one more question, and then I'll turn it over to Paul and others.

524
00:54:08,710 --> 00:54:15,954
Craig, do you actually work with individual homeowners in Massachusetts yet for your lease program?

525
00:54:20,777 --> 00:54:21,257
Go ahead, Craig.

526
00:54:22,138 --> 00:54:27,080
Well, so this has been a topic of live discussion within our company.

527
00:54:30,898 --> 00:54:41,080
The short answer is probably that, yeah, I think our CEO has made it clear that it's his desire that we operate in the single family market.

528
00:54:41,820 --> 00:54:43,881
We have really been focusing on multifamily homes.

529
00:54:43,981 --> 00:54:50,442
That has been our bread and butter, but I think we're open to doing single families.

530
00:54:50,822 --> 00:54:53,763
We plan to do single families, but I think

531
00:54:56,015 --> 00:54:59,016
It's a question of when and how we kick that off.

532
00:55:00,076 --> 00:55:09,298
So I think there are folks here who really want to be on the leading edge of working with block powers, a single family home, that maybe you'd be one of our very first steps.

533
00:55:11,498 --> 00:55:11,618
OK.

534
00:55:12,198 --> 00:55:17,199
Paul, Tez, why don't you ask some of your questions at this time?

535
00:55:18,539 --> 00:55:19,140
Sure.

536
00:55:19,280 --> 00:55:19,840
Can you hear me?

537
00:55:21,040 --> 00:55:21,180
Yes.

538
00:55:22,373 --> 00:55:23,033
Yes, hi.

539
00:55:23,934 --> 00:55:27,795
Thanks so much for your time and effort in putting this in.

540
00:55:28,735 --> 00:55:30,636
Very, very interesting stuff.

541
00:55:30,696 --> 00:55:36,778
Very compelling story from your CEO.

542
00:55:37,018 --> 00:55:40,279
And very much appreciate your time for being here.

543
00:55:41,780 --> 00:55:48,202
So I just wanted to really sort of focus on what this means for the homeowner.

544
00:55:53,071 --> 00:56:09,094
How would you, like, how would you give, can you possibly in any way provide an example of percentage of savings on an utility bill that a homeowner would get?

545
00:56:09,735 --> 00:56:18,096
Is that something that is feasible right now or are there dependencies or whatever?

546
00:56:18,216 --> 00:56:21,097
But if you can just ballpark that,

547
00:56:21,709 --> 00:56:24,630
It would be very good, I think, for homeowners to know that.

548
00:56:27,930 --> 00:56:36,693
Yeah, I'll say if we projected over 10 to 15 years, which is what we normally do, you could see 20 to 40 percent utility bill savings.

549
00:56:37,693 --> 00:56:39,473
You're going to see that in energy savings.

550
00:56:40,833 --> 00:56:41,734
A couple of factors there.

551
00:56:41,754 --> 00:56:46,235
The grid is going to get cleaner and more affordable.

552
00:56:46,555 --> 00:56:48,195
So electricity prices are going to go down.

553
00:56:49,636 --> 00:56:51,536
Oil and natural gas prices are going to go up.

554
00:56:52,705 --> 00:56:53,266
over time.

555
00:56:53,686 --> 00:57:12,902
And so we're projecting against those as well as layering in, I think somebody said that they were in climate or weather, I can't remember what it was, but we're layering in projections on how the climate is going to be impacted in the future by the current level of greenhouse gas emissions and

556
00:57:13,562 --> 00:57:18,425
how hot and warm it's going to get, and cold in the winter it's going to get in the Massachusetts area.

557
00:57:18,465 --> 00:57:20,346
And so we expect to see savings.

558
00:57:20,586 --> 00:57:22,848
And it may not come tomorrow if you switch to heat pump.

559
00:57:22,928 --> 00:57:27,831
But over 10 to 15 years, you should see 20%, if not closer to 40%.

560
00:57:30,092 --> 00:57:30,192
OK.

561
00:57:30,272 --> 00:57:33,695
So these are long-term savings.

562
00:57:33,955 --> 00:57:42,260
And residents should expect to see those long-term savings in their utility bills.

563
00:57:43,535 --> 00:58:03,382
And so I guess the issue comes down to low-income people and moderate-income people who can't really see any kind of increase in their utility bills.

564
00:58:04,062 --> 00:58:11,485
As you probably know, National Grid sent out a notice saying that

565
00:58:12,032 --> 00:58:18,953
we could expect somewhere close to 60% increase in utility bills.

566
00:58:21,614 --> 00:58:41,237
So is there some mechanism to alleviate that from your point of view for homeowners by switching to these energy saving mechanisms that you're proposing?

567
00:58:45,017 --> 00:58:49,019
I mean, unfortunately, both the price of gas and electricity are rising.

568
00:58:50,120 --> 00:58:57,163
And as I understand it, the price of electricity presently is rising higher percentage-wise than the price of gas.

569
00:58:58,383 --> 00:59:00,524
So our systems do run on electricity.

570
00:59:01,225 --> 00:59:07,308
So again, we can't wave a magic wand and limit those costs.

571
00:59:07,408 --> 00:59:09,929
But the nice thing is that residents

572
00:59:11,462 --> 00:59:16,447
can, unlike market rate customers, can get these upgrades for 100% for free.

573
00:59:16,467 --> 00:59:31,162
And again, I think if you're pairing electrification with insulation work, particularly if you, you know, lower income homes are more likely to have issues of deferred maintenance where they may not have good insulation, insulation again 100% paid for,

574
00:59:32,779 --> 00:59:37,503
If you do insulate your home, that definitely lowers your energy costs and lowers your utility bills.

575
00:59:38,104 --> 00:59:46,531
And pairing those two things, you know, might well get you into actually lower utility bill territory presently.

576
00:59:47,932 --> 00:59:57,860
And again, I think when Dennis is talking about saving 20 to 40%, that's including the cost of your lease as part of the, you know,

577
00:59:58,783 --> 01:00:01,745
you know, what you're paying out over the 15 years to the energy.

578
01:00:02,005 --> 01:00:09,990
So when we take that equivalent payments out for folks, you know, I think it comes much quicker, the savings for people.

579
01:00:12,492 --> 01:00:19,977
But yeah, I mean, at the end of the day, unfortunately, like energy of any type is going to be a burden on low income people.

580
01:00:20,337 --> 01:00:27,122
And, you know, I think we have some government programs to assist with that, but I think for some folks, they are not sufficient.

581
01:00:28,632 --> 01:00:28,832
Yeah.

582
01:00:30,412 --> 01:00:42,056
Okay, just to interject, we have a municipal aggregation set up with in Medford, which helps the electrical bills.

583
01:00:42,336 --> 01:00:45,857
So that is, we fortunately have that system in place.

584
01:00:47,677 --> 01:00:47,877
Yep.

585
01:00:48,638 --> 01:00:48,798
Yep.

586
01:00:49,058 --> 01:00:49,338
Thanks.

587
01:00:49,558 --> 01:00:51,098
Thanks so much for that.

588
01:00:52,619 --> 01:00:57,380
So, so are you, I guess, some of the questions that I have from

589
01:00:58,847 --> 01:01:05,772
from our committee is that are you proposing a relationship with the city of Medford?

590
01:01:07,833 --> 01:01:22,143
Do you have in place, you know, relationships with city organizations, city officials in other places?

591
01:01:24,685 --> 01:01:26,867
Do you work with Mass Save?

592
01:01:27,508 --> 01:01:29,369
do you work through Mass Save?

593
01:01:30,610 --> 01:01:32,611
Or is there some sort of synergy there?

594
01:01:35,053 --> 01:01:39,575
You know, just just just ask.

595
01:01:39,595 --> 01:01:41,136
So yes, it is.

596
01:01:41,176 --> 01:01:45,659
Well, so I would say we're not proposing a specific partnership with Medford.

597
01:01:45,699 --> 01:01:52,063
I think we would be eager to discuss what your city's needs are and how we might meet them.

598
01:01:53,544 --> 01:01:53,684
But

599
01:01:54,734 --> 01:01:58,056
We have a customizable menu of what a partnership can look like.

600
01:01:58,096 --> 01:02:14,907
And that's literally runs the gamut from partnering with cities to just sell them our software or sell them our software and electrify five buildings together as a pilot program to a partnership where we're saying we're going to electrify every single building in your city in the next eight years.

601
01:02:15,027 --> 01:02:23,352
So I think what we are not proposing anything particular to Medford, but I think we would be delighted to have a conversation with you all about how we can support

602
01:02:23,705 --> 01:02:28,067
your goals or help you support designing and defining your goals and then executing them.

603
01:02:30,008 --> 01:02:34,250
And yes, to MassSave, we work through and with MassSave.

604
01:02:34,270 --> 01:02:43,715
And so again, any work we do, the MassSave incentives are built into those project costs and used to lower project costs in our end.

605
01:02:45,776 --> 01:02:49,618
So I guess I would, I mean, given your,

606
01:02:52,658 --> 01:02:56,461
your experience in this energy efficiency business.

607
01:02:57,782 --> 01:03:06,249
What is really the primary step that a homeowner can take to save energy?

608
01:03:08,291 --> 01:03:16,318
You come in and make an assessment with residents and whatnot.

609
01:03:16,718 --> 01:03:17,459
What do you think

610
01:03:18,164 --> 01:03:33,617
would be a primary thing that a homeowner can do on their own, for instance, prior to having heat pumps put in and all that stuff.

611
01:03:33,757 --> 01:03:36,039
If you can expand on that, it would be fantastic.

612
01:03:38,621 --> 01:03:41,263
So do you mean what they can do in terms of

613
01:03:42,522 --> 01:03:46,184
like construction work or what they can do in terms of lifestyle changes?

614
01:03:46,224 --> 01:03:47,505
I'm not sure I'm fully capturing.

615
01:03:47,545 --> 01:03:54,290
Oh, no, lifestyle changes or just adding things that a homeowner can do on their own.

616
01:03:54,310 --> 01:03:58,232
What would you suggest?

617
01:03:59,093 --> 01:04:01,854
You mentioned airflow in a house.

618
01:04:04,056 --> 01:04:08,719
Is there some ways that you can propose mitigation of that?

619
01:04:16,447 --> 01:04:16,647
Hello?

620
01:04:18,168 --> 01:04:19,990
I think I'll take a crack at this.

621
01:04:20,831 --> 01:04:23,493
I think this may answer your question.

622
01:04:24,694 --> 01:04:43,550
For homeowners specifically, there are steps you could take to just reduce your overall consumption by making sure your insulated, air sealed systems you have are working properly.

623
01:04:44,493 --> 01:04:49,236
they're maintained, so on and so forth, to reduce your consumption.

624
01:04:49,416 --> 01:04:56,300
That's one side of the equation that we generally are encouraging.

625
01:04:57,580 --> 01:05:09,427
And then beyond that, because a lot of folks who are climate concerned or very aware of their consumption, we're telling folks, go explore these solutions.

626
01:05:09,727 --> 01:05:12,049
There are incentives out there.

627
01:05:12,169 --> 01:05:14,170
There are opportunities out there.

628
01:05:15,288 --> 01:05:17,430
And those things are available today.

629
01:05:17,690 --> 01:05:35,926
And so my greatest piece of advice is I talk to friends and family about this, to our homeowners in the area, is generally just please do not replace a dying fossil fuel system with another fossil fuel system.

630
01:05:37,567 --> 01:05:40,490
Come talk to me next, or come talk to somebody first.

631
01:05:41,956 --> 01:05:43,117
Sure, sure.

632
01:05:43,397 --> 01:05:43,757
Thank you.

633
01:05:44,037 --> 01:05:45,158
Thanks very much.

634
01:05:45,899 --> 01:05:49,281
Gaston looks like he has his hand up.

635
01:05:51,262 --> 01:05:51,602
Yeah, hi.

636
01:05:51,622 --> 01:05:52,083
Thank you.

637
01:05:52,203 --> 01:05:52,543
Thank you.

638
01:05:53,103 --> 01:05:54,945
Yeah, I do have a couple of questions.

639
01:05:55,005 --> 01:06:06,172
So the first one is that I just did a quick search, and I found an article on Green Building Advisor that there seem to be air to water heat pump retrofits that you can do.

640
01:06:07,873 --> 01:06:18,157
I didn't read the whole article, it's pretty long and quite technical, but it seems, so I don't know what the cost would be of that, but it seems that they're available.

641
01:06:18,638 --> 01:06:28,702
And this sounds kind of an interesting proposition for our area, given that I believe that most houses have radiators, either steam or water.

642
01:06:29,402 --> 01:06:37,306
And to me, you know, the idea, what would happen to the radiators if I actually put a forced air system?

643
01:06:38,318 --> 01:06:45,500
And the idea of actually removing them all, removing all the pipes and things like that basically means that I have to open all the walls in my house.

644
01:06:45,520 --> 01:06:49,642
So it's something that I personally, I'm kind of not willing to do.

645
01:06:50,802 --> 01:07:05,427
So I was wondering whether, you know, then having an air to water heat pump where, you know, I can sort of reuse the radiators, it's something that looks a little bit more enticing.

646
01:07:05,907 --> 01:07:06,467
Now, however,

647
01:07:07,043 --> 01:07:13,484
If I do that, then I still would need some other system to pull down the house, if I decide to go that route as well.

648
01:07:14,564 --> 01:07:17,585
So yeah, I don't know.

649
01:07:18,485 --> 01:07:19,905
I am kind of with the same problem.

650
01:07:20,065 --> 01:07:23,886
And I was also wondering between the duct versus duct lift.

651
01:07:23,926 --> 01:07:26,506
So I did a little bit of research on this.

652
01:07:26,606 --> 01:07:36,768
And for the duct system, where I think it would be better for, in my case, the floor where I have all the rooms, so I can avoid having, you know, a mini-flip in each of the rooms.

653
01:07:37,675 --> 01:07:41,237
It seems that you also need a lot of clearance in the room.

654
01:07:41,297 --> 01:07:48,921
So for if your rooms are in the second floor and then you have the attic upstairs, it's actually kind of convenient because you can put all the ducts in the attic.

655
01:07:49,542 --> 01:08:05,491
But then what would happen, for example, in the first floor where, you know, you either have to put them in the basement or if the basement has like, you know, you can actually stand on it, but then it's, let's say like seven feet high, then you would actually lose a lot of height there.

656
01:08:06,906 --> 01:08:27,518
So I was wondering, you know, so for an old house, if you're not planning on sort of redoing your house completely, then what is the optimal way to sort of reuse some of the stuff that you have, in particular the radiators, and make the most efficient use of the space that you currently have in your house?

657
01:08:29,419 --> 01:08:31,500
Yeah, I'll try to distill that down.

658
01:08:32,855 --> 01:08:36,777
a little bit to just kind of give our thoughts on it.

659
01:08:39,658 --> 01:08:58,847
This is why this conversation is really important and this is why the conversations we're having with many different municipalities across the state and across the country and many concerned climate energy groups are talking about this is because

660
01:09:00,170 --> 01:09:14,942
While the technology is now available to put in heat pumps and other things like you mentioned, the cost is a huge barrier and the current existing infrastructure is a big barrier.

661
01:09:16,935 --> 01:09:30,641
If the goal is to have the least impact in terms of how much greenhouse gas emissions you emit, we could propose the most optimal solutions.

662
01:09:32,161 --> 01:09:36,743
If the goal is to have the least construction, there are other solutions like you're mentioning.

663
01:09:37,372 --> 01:09:39,453
out there that are not as commercialized.

664
01:09:39,693 --> 01:09:45,575
And so it really depends on the individual homeowner and the goals and then the budget to be frank.

665
01:09:46,115 --> 01:10:03,882
And we're really hoping that where there is a gap in the budget or the ability to spend incentives and programs like the IRA that is gonna be rolled out federally can help close the gap and make it a no brainer for folks to do the right thing.

666
01:10:05,462 --> 01:10:08,124
OK, and then two quick questions that are left.

667
01:10:08,144 --> 01:10:14,829
So the second one is, in terms of maintenance costs, so I also do have a steam boiler, as Bob has.

668
01:10:15,370 --> 01:10:19,193
And then the maintenance cost of my steam boiler is pretty much minimal.

669
01:10:20,253 --> 01:10:24,197
So I know that you mentioned that for the heat pump, it's actually baked into the lease.

670
01:10:24,297 --> 01:10:31,202
But so what's the average maintenance cost annually for, say, like an average size system

671
01:10:35,604 --> 01:10:35,964
heat pump?

672
01:10:36,824 --> 01:10:41,506
I think that's around three to five hundred dollars.

673
01:10:41,806 --> 01:10:46,628
It is for, you know, a 2,000 square foot home that has two outdoor heat pumps.

674
01:10:46,908 --> 01:10:51,390
Again, Block Power's lease, that's zero dollars on top of the lease that's built in.

675
01:10:53,011 --> 01:10:56,512
But I think, I guess to get back to your earlier question, I do want to

676
01:10:57,460 --> 01:11:05,145
So I skimmed through the article you sent, just to name it, it was a mechanical engineer who undertook the project on his own.

677
01:11:05,906 --> 01:11:09,788
And again, I did not mention the cost involved.

678
01:11:09,848 --> 01:11:15,812
So again, I think it's in theory doable, but it doesn't mean it's commercially viable.

679
01:11:16,927 --> 01:11:22,810
viable yet, unfortunately, particularly at a cost folks are reasonably willing to pay.

680
01:11:23,550 --> 01:11:27,272
But the other thing you referenced, the need to still have AC after this.

681
01:11:27,492 --> 01:11:37,216
And I think that's something really important is that right now, New England is an area that is much more of a heating state than a cooling state.

682
01:11:38,397 --> 01:11:42,779
But unfortunately, as climate change gets worse, that's going to change.

683
01:11:42,859 --> 01:11:45,200
And we're actually going to have more cooling days

684
01:11:46,378 --> 01:11:48,219
in Massachusetts than heating days.

685
01:11:49,559 --> 01:11:55,561
And your air conditioning system is going to become more important than your heating system in terms of maintaining the comfort and livability of your home.

686
01:11:56,421 --> 01:12:05,764
And so again, I think taking the long-term view of investing in a system that allows you to do both, I do think it is a prudent move.

687
01:12:05,944 --> 01:12:10,406
OK, and the last question, I think it wasn't asked.

688
01:12:10,886 --> 01:12:13,887
So in terms of trying to, you know,

689
01:12:15,393 --> 01:12:17,894
going into all electrical for the whole city.

690
01:12:17,914 --> 01:12:22,756
So Medford is about 45% people who rent.

691
01:12:23,256 --> 01:12:37,883
So what's the, what's, how is BlockPower addressing landlords in the sense of what kind of incentives are landlords, can landlords get to sort of electrify the houses that they rent out?

692
01:12:38,123 --> 01:12:38,363
I mean,

693
01:12:38,943 --> 01:12:45,804
not only would that be better for the people that rent it, but then also we need those houses also to switch to electrical eventually.

694
01:12:47,644 --> 01:13:03,727
So all of the incentives that we referenced in terms of $10,000 rebate from Mass Save, the heat loans that are out there, those are all true for landlords as well as for homeowners.

695
01:13:05,247 --> 01:13:08,588
And again, if you're a landowner who has over half of your residents

696
01:13:09,507 --> 01:13:20,673
the residents, the tenants are below the relevant area median income level, then that can be 100% paid for by MassAve.

697
01:13:22,413 --> 01:13:31,918
And the federal government also similarly is looking to incentivize both homeowners and landlords as we're doing this electrification work.

698
01:13:34,459 --> 01:13:36,660
But then as a company, BlockPower, again,

699
01:13:38,731 --> 01:13:46,716
CEO was himself a tenant in a large apartment building and that's definitely a customer base that we are looking to serve our tenants and renters.

700
01:13:48,217 --> 01:13:54,661
And yeah, it's, I'll be lying, be lying if so it's always easy to persuade landlords to undertake these projects.

701
01:13:57,073 --> 01:14:00,455
that there are things you can do.

702
01:14:00,935 --> 01:14:05,837
And I think there are certain types of landlords that are more likely to sign up than others.

703
01:14:05,917 --> 01:14:11,579
And in terms of, again, as we're looking to target our outreach, those are the types of landlords we wanna be reaching out to.

704
01:14:14,401 --> 01:14:18,562
To start, and again, this is a multi-year, multi-step process.

705
01:14:18,602 --> 01:14:24,585
And so go with those who are gonna be easiest to get first as the early adopters and go on from there.

706
01:14:26,286 --> 01:14:30,051
Yeah, and our strategy for that for block power historically has been.

707
01:14:32,383 --> 01:14:45,131
deep community engagement, understanding who the landlords are, what's their involvement in the community, how do we make their lives easier potentially with our lease and covering O&M like Craig was talking about.

708
01:14:46,532 --> 01:14:56,758
But it really does take a huge effort by everybody involved to educate, to incentivize and to get folks to make that switch.

709
01:14:58,399 --> 01:14:59,300
Yeah, we haven't,

710
01:14:59,945 --> 01:15:08,187
Unfortunately, we haven't created some magical program that gives landlords a bunch of extra money and solves all of the challenges yet.

711
01:15:08,227 --> 01:15:09,567
We're working on it, though.

712
01:15:12,428 --> 01:15:12,668
Great.

713
01:15:12,788 --> 01:15:13,488
Thanks, guys.

714
01:15:14,028 --> 01:15:22,170
I think in the last 5 to 10 minutes here, I have two more questions that came in over email from a resident.

715
01:15:22,490 --> 01:15:23,890
And I'll package that together.

716
01:15:23,910 --> 01:15:25,190
I think they'll be fairly quick for you.

717
01:15:25,250 --> 01:15:27,771
And then for the last few minutes, I'll

718
01:15:28,740 --> 01:15:33,223
any other committee members or ask any remaining questions that they have.

719
01:15:33,383 --> 01:15:48,993
But the resident who sent in a list of questions, there is some interest in knowing where the T-Pump technology is manufactured, whether that's in the United States or somewhere else.

720
01:15:49,253 --> 01:15:57,959
And then also, if someone was going to have this installed at their home, how long would it take for that work to be completed?

721
01:16:03,300 --> 01:16:10,926
I honestly don't know where the heat pumps that we source are made.

722
01:16:11,006 --> 01:16:16,750
We do have direct manufacturer relationships with Mitsubishi and Fujitsu among others.

723
01:16:18,732 --> 01:16:25,376
I'd be surprised if they don't have some domestic plants that are manufacturing them, but I don't know that confidently.

724
01:16:29,419 --> 01:16:29,840
In terms of

725
01:16:31,722 --> 01:16:32,943
how long it would take to do the work.

726
01:16:34,965 --> 01:17:00,004
I mean, you know, it should be, I guess it depends on when you're starting, you know, when you're just, you know, there's time to design the system and, you know, the first visit, if you're willing to sign a contract that same day, I think, you know, the heat pump could be installed within your home within a month or two, but it kind of depends on, again, on the exact system that you want.

727
01:17:00,224 --> 01:17:01,025
And, you know, there are,

728
01:17:01,850 --> 01:17:12,598
likely going to be some supply chain issues that we're projecting just as, you know, I think as we enter 2023 and there's more federal incentives, you know, there are already some supply chain issues across the board.

729
01:17:12,659 --> 01:17:21,726
And I think if there's a spike in heat pump purchasing because of these new incentives, you know, that could slow things down.

730
01:17:21,766 --> 01:17:24,708
We don't know exactly how that will play out.

731
01:17:26,489 --> 01:17:31,413
But yeah, I think the sooner you get in the queue, the sooner you'll get your heat pumps installed.

732
01:17:34,570 --> 01:17:35,831
All right, thank you.

733
01:17:37,211 --> 01:17:41,933
To the Energy and Environment Committee members that are still on the call, any more questions?

734
01:17:47,295 --> 01:17:47,795
Can you hear me?

735
01:17:49,756 --> 01:17:50,516
Sure, Paul, go ahead.

736
01:17:51,597 --> 01:17:54,998
What would be your pitch to a low-income person who lives in

737
01:18:03,218 --> 01:18:12,181
the house, and is struggling to, you know, meet the energy bills, what would be your pitch?

738
01:18:12,801 --> 01:18:30,247
And I know, you see that the issue with with taking on all of this stuff is, is that is that is that people are so concerned about, you know, paying bills the next day,

739
01:18:31,539 --> 01:18:44,731
that you kind of, like climate change is a secondary issue or might be even a tertiary issue.

740
01:18:46,012 --> 01:18:51,938
So how would you, and I know this is a tough question.

741
01:18:52,098 --> 01:18:56,262
I'm somewhat sorry asking it, but you know,

742
01:18:57,065 --> 01:18:58,446
You, you are here.

743
01:18:58,466 --> 01:19:02,349
And I hope, I hope you have some answer for this.

744
01:19:02,410 --> 01:19:03,691
But you know, you have to.

745
01:19:03,711 --> 01:19:15,360
I mean, you are trying to change, introduce change in our conception of energy usage.

746
01:19:16,141 --> 01:19:20,044
So how would you how would you pitch that to a to a low income person?

747
01:19:21,765 --> 01:19:21,886
So,

748
01:19:23,407 --> 01:19:25,628
I can take it first step, Dennis, feel free to jump in.

749
01:19:26,048 --> 01:19:35,012
So first, again, I would just highlight, you know, depending again on their income levels, how much of this work could be free for them to have installed.

750
01:19:37,233 --> 01:19:41,414
And say, you know, things like insulation are guaranteed money savers for them.

751
01:19:41,715 --> 01:19:47,577
If they just want to insulate, you know, that's a great thing that, you know, is a slam dunk for them.

752
01:19:48,798 --> 01:19:52,741
But I think the other things I would talk about are things like health and comfort, right?

753
01:19:53,922 --> 01:20:05,031
That if you're talking about making the air in your home healthier for your family, that's a hard thing to put a price on.

754
01:20:05,111 --> 01:20:14,698
Any parent who's ever watched their child struggle to breathe can intimately understand how they want to make that air as clean and healthy as possible for their kid.

755
01:20:15,560 --> 01:20:29,731
And, you know, particularly if these are homes with, again, issues of deferred maintenance, where if they've got mold or asbestos or jeopardizing the health of their family, you know, there are steps to take to remediate.

756
01:20:30,051 --> 01:20:35,015
There are some incentives for remediation, not perfect incentives, not for all types of remediation.

757
01:20:36,657 --> 01:20:38,238
But yeah, I think that's a big part of it.

758
01:20:38,318 --> 01:20:43,542
And again, I think as you look to the comfort level, right, that heat waves are going to be an increasingly

759
01:20:44,577 --> 01:20:48,780
prominent part of our lived experience in the coming years and decades.

760
01:20:49,941 --> 01:21:04,353
And again, having cooling systems is both a thing to make your home life more comfortable if you don't currently have cooling, but also, again, I think increasingly, we're gonna start seeing air conditioning as a human right.

761
01:21:04,873 --> 01:21:11,539
You see heat in the winter as a human right, where it's just something you need to survive.

762
01:21:12,212 --> 01:21:17,176
because it's going to increasingly get hot where lives are jeopardized by not having cooling units.

763
01:21:17,496 --> 01:21:36,029
And, you know, being able to bring that into the home, I think, is another point that's, again, hard to kind of put a price on that level of comfort and health, as well as, again, the benefits of not condemning humanity to a worse fate, if you're able to do your part on that.

764
01:21:37,770 --> 01:21:38,431
Sure, sure.

765
01:21:39,371 --> 01:21:41,073
I very much appreciate your answer.

766
01:21:41,093 --> 01:21:41,413
Thank you.

767
01:21:47,585 --> 01:21:53,009
Hello.

768
01:21:53,049 --> 01:21:53,509
Thanks, guys.

769
01:21:53,589 --> 01:21:54,830
And anything else, Bob?

770
01:21:55,790 --> 01:21:59,553
I think we're getting close to the end of the hour and a half anyway.

771
01:21:59,933 --> 01:22:08,098
